    "k, go close to the water beyond the storehouses. I will be there with a man to remove your chain"
    "s. But keep your faces well covered and do not stop. He will think you slaves.\342\200\235\n\nWi"
    "th that he passed some rags to them, holding his hands behind his back, while they stood close t"
    "o him. Then he turned and hurried back. Very slowly Feversham and Trench walked forwards in the "
    "direction of the prison; the dusk crept across the river, mounted the long slope of sand, envelo"
    "ped them. They sat down and quickly wrapped the rags about their chains and secured them there. "
    "From the west the colours of the sunset had altogether faded, the darkness gathered quickly abou"
    "t them. They turned and walked back along the road they had come. The drums were more numerous n"
    "ow, and above the wall there rose a glare of light. By the time they had reached the water\342"
    "\200\231s edge opposite the storehouses it was dark. Abou Fatma was already waiting with his bla"
    "cksmith. The chains were knocked off without a word spoken.\n\n\342\200\234Come,\342\200\235 sai"
    "d Abou . \342\200\234There will be no moon tonight. How long before they discover you are gone?"
    "\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Who knows? Perhaps already Idris has missed us. Perhaps he will not "
    "till morning. There are many prisoners.\342\200\235\n\nThey ran up the slope of sand, between th"
    "e quarters of the tribes, across the narrow width of the city, through the cemetery. On the far "
    "side of the cemetery stood a disused house; a man rose up in the doorway as they approached, and"
    " went in.\n\n\342\200\234Wait here,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma , and he too went into the house"
    ". In a moment both men came back, and each one led a camel and made it kneel.\n\n\342\200\234Mou"
    "nt,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma . \342\200\234Bring its head round and hold it as you mount.\342"
    "\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I know the trick,\342\200\235 said Trench.\n\nFeversham climbed up behin"
    "d him, the two Arabs mounted the second camel.\n\n\342\200\234Ten miles to the west,\342\200\235"
    " said Abou Fatma , and he struck the camel on the flanks.\n\nBehind them the glare of the lights"
    " dwindled, the tapping of the drums diminished.";

static const char generated_chapter_content_029[] =
    "The wind blew keen and cold from the north. The camels, freshened by it, trotted out at their fa"
    "stest pace.\n\n\342\200\234Quicker,\342\200\235 said Trench, between his teeth. \342\200\234Alre"
    "ady Idris may have missed us.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Even if he has,\342\200\235 replied Fev"
    "ersham, \342\200\234it will take time to get men together for a pursuit, and those men must fetc"
    "h their camels, and already it is dark.\342\200\235\n\nBut although he spoke hopefully, he turne"
    "d his head again and again towards the glare of light above Omdurman. He could no longer hear th"
    "e tapping of the drums, that was some consolation. But he was in a country of silence, where men"
    " could journey swiftly and yet make no noise. There would be no sound of galloping horses to war"
    "n him that pursuit was at his heels. Even at that moment the Ansar soldiers might be riding with"
    "in thirty paces of them, and Feversham strained his eyes backwards into the darkness and expecte"
    "d the glimmer of a white turban. Trench, however, never turned his head. He rode with his teeth "
    "set, looking forward. Yet fear was no less strong in him than in Feversham. Indeed, it was stron"
    "ger, for he did not look back towards Omdurman because he did not dare; and though his eyes were"
    " fixed directly in front of him, the things which he really saw were the long narrow streets of "
    "the town behind him, the dotted fires at the corners of the streets, and men running hither and "
    "thither among the houses, making their quick search for the two prisoners escaped from the House"
    " of Stone.\n\nOnce his attention was diverted by a word from Feversham, and he answered without "
    "turning his head:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234What is it?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I no longer "
    "see the fires of Omdurman.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234The golden blot, eh, very low down?\342"
    "\200\235 Trench answered in an abstracted voice. Feversham did not ask him to explain what his a"
    "llusion meant, nor could Trench have disclosed why he had spoken it; the words had come back to "
    "him suddenly with a feeling that it was somehow appropriate that the vision which was the last t"
    "hing to meet Feversham\342\200\231s eyes as he set out upon his mission he should see again now "
    "that that mission was accomplished. They spoke no more until two figures rose out of the darknes"
    "s in front of them, at the very feet of their camels, and Abou Fatma cried in a low voice:\342"
    "\200\224\n\n\342\200\234 Instanna! \342\200\235\n\nThey halted their camels and made them kneel."
    "\n\n\342\200\234The new camels are here?\342\200\235 asked Abou Fatma , and two of the men disap"
    "peared for a few minutes and brought four camels up. Meanwhile the saddles were unfastened and r"
    "emoved from the camels Trench and his companion had ridden out of Omdurman.\n\n\342\200\234They "
    "are good camels?\342\200\235 asked Feversham, as he helped to fix the saddles upon the fresh one"
    "s.\n\n\342\200\234Of the Anafi breed,\342\200\235 answered Abou Fatma . \342\200\234Quick! Quick"
    "!\342\200\235 and he looked anxiously to the east and listened.\n\n\342\200\234The arms?\342\200"
    "\235 said Trench. \342\200\234You have them? Where are they?\342\200\235 and he bent his body an"
    "d searched the ground for them.\n\n\342\200\234In a moment,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma , but it"
    " seemed that Trench could hardly wait for that moment to arrive. He showed even more anxiety to "
    "handle the weapons than he had shown fear that he would be overtaken.\n\n\342\200\234There is am"
    "munition?\342\200\235 he asked feverishly.\n\n\342\200\234Yes, yes,\342\200\235 replied Abou Fat"
    "ma , \342\200\234ammunition and rifles and revolvers.\342\200\235 He led the way to a spot about"
    " twenty yards from the camels, where some long desert grass rustled about their legs. He stooped"
    " and dug into the soft sand with his hands.\n\n\342\200\234Here,\342\200\235 he said.\n\nTrench "
    "flung himself upon the ground beside him and scooped with both hands, making all the while an in"
    "human whimpering sound with his mouth, like the noise a foxhound makes at a cover. There was som"
    "ething rather horrible to Feversham in his attitude as he scraped at the ground on his knees, at"
    " the action of his hands, quick like the movements of a dog\342\200\231s paws, and in the whine "
    "of his voice. He was sunk for the time into an animal. In a moment or two Trench\342\200\231s fi"
    "ngers touched the lock and trigger of a rifle, and he became man again. He stood up quietly with"
    " the rifle in his hands. The other arms were unearthed, the ammunition shared.\n\n\342\200\234No"
    "w,\342\200\235 said Trench, and he laughed with a great thrill of joy in the laugh. \342\200\234"
    "Now I don\342\200\231t mind. Let them follow from Omdurman! One thing is certain now: I shall ne"
    "ver go back there; no, not even if they overtake us,\342\200\235 and he fondled the rifle which "
    "he held and spoke to it as though it lived.\n\nTwo of the Arabs mounted the old camels and rode "
    "slowly away to Omdurman. Abou Fatma and the other remained with the fugitives. They mounted and "
    "trotted northeastwards. No more than a quarter of an hour had elapsed since they had first halte"
    "d at Abou Fatma \342\200\231s word.\n\nAll that night they rode through halfa grass and mimosa t"
    "rees and went but slowly, but they came about sunrise on to flat, bare ground broken with small "
    "hillocks.\n\n\342\200\234Are the Effendi tired?\342\200\235 asked Abou Fatma . \342\200\234Will "
    "they stop and eat? There is food upon the saddle of each camel.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234No; w"
    "e can eat as we go.\342\200\235\n\nDates and bread and a draught of water from a water bottle ma"
    "de up their meal, and they ate it as they sat their camels. These, indeed, now that they were fr"
    "ee of the long desert grass, trotted at their quickest pace. And at sunset that evening they sto"
    "pped and rested for an hour. All through that night they rode and the next day, straining their "
    "own endurance and that of the beasts they were mounted on, now ascending on to high and rocky gr"
    "ound, now traversing a valley, and now trotting fast across plains of honey-coloured sand. Yet t"
    "o each man the pace seemed always as slow as a funeral. A mountain would lift itself above the r"
    "im of the horizon at sunrise, and for the whole livelong day it stood before their eyes, and was"
    " never a foot higher or an inch nearer. At times, some men tilling a scanty patch of sorghum wou"
    "ld send the fugitives\342\200\231 hearts leaping in their throats, and they must make a wide det"
    "our; or again a caravan would be sighted in the far distance by the keen eyes of Abou Fatma , an"
    "d they made their camels kneel and lay crouched behind a rock, with their loaded rifles in their"
    " hands. Ten miles from Abu Klea a relay of fresh camels awaited them, and upon these they travel"
    "led, keeping a day\342\200\231s march westward of the Nile. Thence they passed through the deser"
    "t country of the Ababdeh , and came in sight of a broad grey tract stretching across their path."
    "\n\n\342\200\234The road from Berber to Merowi ,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma . \342\200\234North"
    " of it we turn east to the river. We cross that road tonight; and if God wills, tomorrow evening"
    " we shall have crossed the Nile.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234If God wills,\342\200\235 said Trenc"
    "h. \342\200\234If only He wills,\342\200\235 and he glanced about him in a fear which only incre"
    "ased the nearer they drew towards safety. They were in a country traversed by the caravans; it w"
    "as no longer safe to travel by day. They dismounted, and all that day they lay hidden behind a b"
    "elt of shrubs upon some high ground and watched the road and the people like specks moving along"
    " it. They came down and crossed it in the darkness, and for the rest of that night travelled har"
    "d towards the river. As the day broke Abou Fatma again bade them halt. They were in a desolate o"
    "pen country, whereon the smallest protection was magnified by the surrounding flatness. Feversha"
    "m and Trench gazed eagerly to their right. Somewhere in that direction and within the range of t"
    "heir eyesight flowed the Nile, but they could not see it.\n\n\342\200\234We must build a circle "
    "of stones,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma , \342\200\234and you must lie close to the ground within"
    " it. I will go forward to the river, and see that the boat is ready and that our friends are pre"
    "pared for us. I shall come back after dark.\342\200\235\n\nThey gathered the stones quickly and "
    "made a low wall about a foot high; within this wall Feversham and Trench laid themselves down up"
    "on the ground with a water-skin and their rifles at their sides.\n\n\342\200\234You have dates, "
    "too,\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma .\n\n\342\200\234Yes.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Then do not st"
    "ir from the hiding-place till I come back. I will take your camels, and bring you back fresh one"
    "s in the evening.\342\200\235 And in company with his fellow Arab he rode off towards the river."
    "\n\nTrench and Feversham dug out the sand within the stones and lay down, watching the horizon b"
    "etween the interstices. For both of them this perhaps was the longest day of their lives. They w"
    "ere so near to safety and yet not safe. To Trench\342\200\231s thinking it was longer than a nig"
    "ht in the House of Stone, and to Feversham longer than even one of those days six years back whe"
    "n he had sat in his rooms above St. James\342\200\231s Park and waited for the night to fall bef"
    "ore he dared venture out into the streets. They were so near to Berber, and the pursuit must nee"
    "ds be close behind. Feversham lay wondering how he had ever found the courage to venture himself"
    " in Berber. They had no shade to protect them; all day the sun burnt pitilessly upon their backs"
    ", and within the narrow circle of stones they had no room wherein to move. They spoke hardly at "
    "all. The sunset, however, came at the last, the friendly darkness gathered about them, and a coo"
    "l wind rustled through the darkness across the desert.\n\n\342\200\234Listen!\342\200\235 said T"
    "rench; and both men as they strained their ears heard the soft padding of camels very near at ha"
    "nd. A moment later a low whistle brought them out of their shelter.\n\n\342\200\234We are here,"
    "\342\200\235 said Feversham, quietly.\n\n\342\200\234God be thanked!\342\200\235 said Abou Fatma"
    " . \342\200\234I have good news for you, and bad news too. The boat is ready, our friends are wa"
    "iting for us, camels are prepared for you on the caravan track by the riverbank to Abu Hamed . B"
    "ut your escape is known, and the roads and the ferries are closely watched. Before sunrise we mu"
    "st have struck inland from the eastern bank of the Nile.\342\200\235\n\nThey crossed the river c"
    "autiously about one o\342\200\231clock of the morning, and sank the boat upon the far side of th"
    "e stream. The camels were waiting for them, and they travelled inland and more slowly than suite"
    "d the anxiety of the fugitives. For the ground was thickly covered with boulders, and the camels"
    " could seldom proceed at any pace faster than a walk. And all through the next day they lay hidd"
    "en again within a ring of stones while the camels were removed to some high ground where they co"
    "uld graze. During the next night, however, they made good progress, and, coming to the groves of"
    " Abu Hamed in two days, rested for twelve hours there and mounted upon a fresh relay. From Abu H"
    "amed their road lay across the great Nubian Desert.\n\nNowadays the traveller may journey throug"
    "h the two hundred and forty miles of that waterless plain of coal-black rocks and yellow sand, a"
    "nd sleep in his berth upon the way. The morning will show to him, perhaps, a tent, a great pile "
    "of coal, a water tank, and a number painted on a white signboard, and the stoppage of the train "
    "will inform him that he has come to a station. Let him put his head from the window, he will see"
    " the long line of telegraph poles reaching from the sky\342\200\231s rim behind him to the sky"
    "\342\200\231s rim in front, and huddling together, as it seems, with less and less space between"
    " them the farther they are away. Twelve hours will enclose the beginning and the end of his jour"
    "ney, unless the engine break down or the rail be blocked. But in the days when Feversham and Tre"
    "nch escaped from Omdurman progression was not so easy a matter. They kept eastward of the presen"
    "t railway and along the line of wells among the hills. And on the second night of this stage of "
    "their journey Trench shook Feversham by the shoulders and waked him up.\n\n\342\200\234Look,\342"
    "\200\235 he said, and he pointed to the south. \342\200\234Tonight there\342\200\231s no Souther"
    "n Cross.\342\200\235 His voice broke with emotion. \342\200\234For six years, for every night of"
    " six years, until this night, I have seen the Southern Cross. How often have I lain awake watchi"
    "ng it, wondering whether the night would ever come when I should not see those four slanting sta"
    "rs! I tell you, Feversham, this is the first moment when I have really dared to think that we sh"
    "ould escape.\342\200\235\n\nBoth men sat up and watched the southern sky with prayers of thankfu"
    "lness in their hearts; and when they fell asleep it was only to wake up again and again with a f"
    "ear that they would after all still see that constellation blazing low down towards the earth, a"
    "nd to fall asleep again confident of the issue of their desert ride. At the end of seven days th"
    "ey came to Shof-el-Ain , a tiny well set in a barren valley between featureless ridges, and by t"
    "he side of that well they camped. They were in the country of the Amrab Arabs, and had come to a"
    "n end of their peril.\n\n\342\200\234We are safe,\342\200\235 cried Abou Fatma . \342\200\234God"
    " is good. Northwards to Assouan , westwards to Wadi Halfa , we are safe!\342\200\235 And spreadi"
    "ng a cloth upon the ground in front of the kneeling camels, he heaped dhurra before them. He eve"
    "n went so far in his gratitude as to pat one of the animals upon the neck, and it immediately tu"
    "rned upon him and snarled.\n\nTrench reached out his hand to Feversham.\n\n\342\200\234Thank you"
    ",\342\200\235 he said simply.\n\n\342\200\234No need of thanks,\342\200\235 answered Feversham, "
    "and he did not take the hand. \342\200\234I served myself from first to last.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234You have learned the churlishness of a camel,\342\200\235 cried Trench. \342\200\234"
    "A camel will carry you where you want to go, will carry you till it drops dead, and yet if you s"
    "how your gratitude it resents and bites. Hang it all, Feversham, there\342\200\231s my hand.\342"
    "\200\235\n\nFeversham untied a knot in the breast of his jibbeh and took out three white feather"
    "s, two small, the feathers of a heron, the other large, an ostrich feather broken from a fan.\n"
    "\n\342\200\234Will you take yours back?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234You know what to do with it.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. There shall be no delay.\342"
    "\200\235\n\nFeversham wrapped the remaining feathers carefully away in a corner of his ragged ji"
    "bbeh and tied them safe.\n\n\342\200\234We shake hands, then,\342\200\235 said he; and as their "
    "hands met he added, \342\200\234Tomorrow morning we part company.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Par"
    "t company, you and I\342\200\224after the year in Omdurman, the weeks of flight?\342\200\235 exc"
    "laimed Trench. \342\200\234Why? There\342\200\231s no more to be done. Castleton\342\200\231s de"
    "ad. You keep the feather which he sent, but he is dead. You can do nothing with it. You must com"
    "e home.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 answered Feversham, \342\200\234but after yo"
    "u, certainly not with you. You go on to Assouan and Cairo. At each place you will find friends t"
    "o welcome you. I shall not go with you.\342\200\235\n\nTrench was silent for a while. He underst"
    "ood Feversham\342\200\231s reluctance, he saw that it would be easier for Feversham if he were t"
    "o tell his story first to Ethne Eustace, and without Feversham\342\200\231s presence.\n\n\342"
    "\200\234I ought to tell you no one knows why you resigned your commission, or of the feathers we"
    " sent. We never spoke of it. We agreed never to speak, for the honour of the regiment. I can\342"
    "\200\231t tell you how glad I am that we all agreed and kept to the agreement,\342\200\235 he sa"
    "id.\n\n\342\200\234Perhaps you will see Durrance,\342\200\235 said Feversham; \342\200\234if you"
    " do, give him a message from me. Tell him that the next time he asks me to come and see him, whe"
    "ther it is in England or Wadi Halfa , I will accept the invitation.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234W"
    "hich way will you go?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234To Wadi Halfa ,\342\200\235 said Feversham, poi"
    "nting westwards over his shoulder. \342\200\234I shall take Abou Fatma with me and travel slowly"
    " and quietly down the Nile. The other Arab will guide you into Assouan .\342\200\235\n\nThey sle"
    "pt that night in security beside the well, and the next morning they parted company. Trench was "
    "the first to ride off, and as his camel rose to its feet, ready for the start, he bent down towa"
    "rds Feversham, who passed him the nose rein.\n\n\342\200\234Ramelton, that was the name? I shall"
    " not forget.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes, Ramelton,\342\200\235 said Feversham; \342\200\234t"
    "here\342\200\231s a ferry across Lough Swilly to Rathmullen. You must drive the twelve miles to "
    "Ramelton. But you may not find her there.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234If not there, I shall find "
    "her somewhere else. Make no mistake, Feversham, I shall find her.\342\200\235\n\nAnd Trench rode"
    " forward, alone with his Arab guide. More than once he turned his head and saw Feversham still s"
    "tanding by the well; more than once he was strongly drawn to stop and ride back to that solitary"
    " figure, but he contented himself with waving his hand, and even that salute was not returned.\n"
    "\nFeversham, indeed, had neither thought nor eyes for the companion of his flight. His six years"
    " of hard probation had come this morning to an end, and yet he was more sensible of a certain lo"
    "ss and vacancy than of any joy. For six years, through many trials, through many falterings, his"
    " mission had strengthened and sustained him. It seemed to him now that there was nothing more wh"
    "erewith to occupy his life. Ethne? No doubt she was long since married \342\200\246 and there ca"
    "me upon him all at once a great bitterness of despair for that futile, unnecessary mistake made "
    "by him six years ago. He saw again the room in London overlooking the quiet trees and lawns of S"
    "t. James\342\200\231s Park, he heard the knock upon the door, he took the telegram from his serv"
    "ant\342\200\231s hand.\n\nHe roused himself finally with the recollection that, after all, the w"
    "ork was not quite done. There was his father, who just at this moment was very likely reading Th"
    "e Times after breakfast upon the terrace of Broad Place among the pine trees upon the Surrey hil"
    "ls. He must visit his father, he must take that fourth feather back to Ramelton. There was a tel"
    "egram, too, which must be sent to Lieutenant Sutch at Suakin.\n\nHe mounted his camel and rode s"
    "lowly with Abou Fatma westwards towards Wadi Halfa . But the sense of loss did not pass from him"
    " that day, nor his anger at the act of folly which had brought about his downfall. The wooded sl"
    "opes of Ramelton were very visible to him across the shimmer of the desert air. In the greatness"
    " of his depression Harry Feversham upon this day, for the first time, doubted his faith in the "
    "\342\200\234afterwards.\342\200\235";

static const char generated_chapter_content_030[] =
    "On an August morning of the same year Harry Feversham rode across the Lennon bridge into Ramelto"
    "n. The fierce suns of the Sudan had tanned his face, the years of his probation had left their m"
    "arks; he rode up the narrow street of the town unrecognised. At the top of the hill he turned in"
    "to the broad highway which, descending valleys and climbing hills, runs in one straight line to "
    "Letterkenny. He rode rather quickly in a company of ghosts.\n\nThe intervening years had gradual"
    "ly been dropping from his thoughts all through his journey across Egypt and the Continent. They "
    "were no more than visionary now. Nor was he occupied with any dream of the things which might ha"
    "ve been but for his great fault. The things which had been, here, in this small town of Ireland,"
    " were too definite. Here he had been most happy, here he had known the uttermost of his misery; "
    "here his presence had brought pleasure, here too he had done his worst harm. Once he stopped whe"
    "n he was opposite to the church, set high above the road upon his right hand, and wondered wheth"
    "er Ethne was still at Ramelton\342\200\224whether old Dermod was alive, and what kind of welcome"
    " he would receive. But he woke in a moment to the knowledge that he was sitting upon his horse i"
    "n the empty road and in the quiet of an August morning. There were larks singing in the pale blu"
    "e above his head; a landrail sent up its harsh cry from the meadow on the left; the crow of a co"
    "ck rose clear from the valley. He looked about him, and rode briskly on down the incline in fron"
    "t of him and up the ascent beyond. He rode again with his company of ghosts\342\200\224phantoms "
    "of people with whom upon this road he had walked and ridden and laughed, ghosts of old thoughts "
    "and recollected words. He came to a thick grove of trees, a broken fence, a gateway with no gate"
    ". Inattentive to these evidences of desertion, he turned in at the gate and rode along a weedy a"
    "nd neglected drive. At the end of it he came to an open space before a ruined house. The aspect "
    "of the tumbling walls and unroofed rooms roused him at last completely from his absorption. He d"
    "ismounted, and, tying his horse to the branch of a tree, ran quickly into the house and called a"
    "loud. No voice answered him. He ran from deserted room to deserted room. He descended into the g"
    "arden, but no one came to meet him; and he understood now from the uncut grass upon the lawn, th"
    "e tangled disorder of the flowerbeds, that no one would come. He mounted his horse again, and ro"
    "de back at a sharp trot. In Ramelton he stopped at the inn, gave his horse to the ostler, and or"
    "dered lunch for himself. He said to the landlady who waited upon him:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200"
    "\234So Lennon House has been burned down? When was that?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Five years a"
    "go,\342\200\235 the landlady returned, \342\200\234just five years ago this summer.\342\200\235 "
    "And she proceeded, without further invitation, to give a voluminous account of the conflagration"
    " and the cause of it, the ruin of the Eustace family, the inebriety of Bastable, and the death o"
    "f Dermod Eustace at Glenalla. \342\200\234But we hope to see the house rebuilt. It\342\200\231s "
    "likely to be, we hear, when Miss Eustace is married,\342\200\235 she said, in a voice which sugg"
    "ested that she was full of interesting information upon the subject of Miss Eustace\342\200\231s"
    " marriage. Her guest, however, did not respond to the invitation.\n\n\342\200\234And where does "
    "Miss Eustace live now?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234At Glenalla,\342\200\235 she replied. \342\200"
    "\234Halfway on the road to Rathmullen there\342\200\231s a track leads up to your left. It\342"
    "\200\231s a poor mountain village is Glenalla, and no place for Miss Eustace, at all, at all. Pe"
    "rhaps you will be wanting to see her?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. I shall be glad if you wil"
    "l order my horse to be brought round to the door,\342\200\235 said the man; and he rose from the"
    " table to put an end to the interview.\n\nThe landlady, however, was not so easily dismissed. Sh"
    "e stood at the door and remarked:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234Well, that\342\200\231s curious\342"
    "\200\224that\342\200\231s most curious. For only a fortnight ago a gentleman burnt just as black"
    " as yourself stayed a night here on the same errand. He asked for Miss Eustace\342\200\231s addr"
    "ess and drove up to Glenalla. Perhaps you have business with her?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes"
    ", I have business with Miss Eustace,\342\200\235 the stranger returned. \342\200\234Will you be "
    "good enough to give orders about my horse?\342\200\235\n\nWhile he was waiting for his horse he "
    "looked through the leaves of the hotel book, and saw under a date towards the end of July the na"
    "me of Colonel Trench.\n\n\342\200\234You will come back, sir, tonight?\342\200\235 said the land"
    "lady, as he mounted.\n\n\342\200\234No,\342\200\235 he answered, \342\200\234I do not think I sh"
    "all come again to Ramelton.\342\200\235 And he rode down the hill, and once more that day crosse"
    "d the Lennon bridge. Four miles on he came to the track opposite a little bay of the Lough, and,"
    " turning into it, he rode past a few white cottages up to the purple hollow of the hills. It was"
    " about five o\342\200\231clock when he came to the long, straggling village. It seemed very quie"
    "t and deserted, and built without any plan. A few cottages stood together, then came a gap of fi"
    "elds, beyond that a small plantation of larches and a house which stood by itself. Beyond the ho"
    "use was another gap, through which he could see straight down to the water of the Lough, shining"
    " in the afternoon sun, and the white gulls poising and swooping above it. And after passing that"
    " gap he came to a small grey church, standing bare to the winds upon its tiny plateau. A pathway"
    " of white shell-dust led from the door of the church to the little wooden gate. As he came level"
    " with the gate a collie dog barked at him from behind it.\n\nThe rider looked at the dog, which "
    "was very grey about the muzzle. He noticed its marking, and stopped his horse altogether. He gla"
    "nced towards the church, and saw that the door stood open. At once he dismounted; he fastened hi"
    "s horse to the fence, and entered the churchyard. The collie thrust its muzzle into the back of "
    "his knee, sniffed once or twice doubtfully, and suddenly broke into an exuberant welcome. The co"
    "llie dog had a better memory than the landlady of the inn. He barked, wagged his tail, crouched "
    "and sprang at the stranger\342\200\231s shoulders, whirled round and round in front of him, burs"
    "t into sharp, excited screams of pleasure, ran up to the church door and barked furiously there,"
    " then ran back and jumped again upon his friend. The man caught the dog as it stood up with its "
    "forepaws upon his chest, patted it, and laughed. Suddenly he ceased laughing, and stood stock-st"
    "ill with his eyes towards the open door of the church. In the doorway Ethne Eustace was standing"
    ". He put the dog down and slowly walked up the path towards her. She waited on the threshold wit"
    "hout moving, without speaking. She waited, watching him, until he came close to her. Then she sa"
    "id simply:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234Harry.\342\200\235\n\nShe was silent after that; nor did h"
    "e speak. All the ghosts and phantoms of old thoughts in whose company he had travelled the whole"
    " of that day vanished away from his mind at her simple utterance of his name. Six years had pass"
    "ed since his feet crushed the gravel on the dawn of a June morning beneath her window. And they "
    "looked at one another, remarking the changes which those six years had brought. And the changes,"
    " unnoticed and almost imperceptible to those who had lived daily in their company, sprang very d"
    "istinct to the eyes of these two. Feversham was thin, his face was wasted. The strain of life in"
    " the House of Stone had left its signs about his sunken eyes and in the look of age beyond his y"
    "ears. But these were not the only changes, as Ethne noticed; they were not, indeed, the most imp"
    "ortant ones. Her heart, although she stood so still and silent, went out to him in grief for the"
    " great troubles which he had endured; but she saw, too, that he came back without a thought of a"
    "nger towards her for that fourth feather snapped from her fan. But she was clear-eyed even at th"
    "is moment. She saw much more. She understood that the man who stood quietly before her now was n"
    "ot the same man whom she had last seen in the hall of Ramelton. There had been a timidity in his"
    " manner in those days, a peculiar diffidence, a continual expectation of other men\342\200\231s "
    "contempt, which had gone from him. He was now quietly self-possessed; not arrogant; on the other"
    " hand, not diffident. He had put himself to a long, hard test; and he knew that he had not faile"
    "d. All that she saw; and her face lightened as she said:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234It is not al"
    "l harm which has come of these years. They were not wasted.\342\200\235\n\nBut Feversham thought"
    " of her lonely years in this village of Glenalla\342\200\224and thought with a man\342\200\231s "
    "thought, unaware that nowhere else would she have chosen to live. He looked into her face, and s"
    "aw the marks of the years upon it. It was not that she had aged so much. Her big grey eyes shone"
    " as clearly as before, the colour was still as bright upon her cheeks. But there was more of cha"
    "racter. She had suffered; she had eaten of the tree of knowledge.\n\n\342\200\234I am sorry,\342"
    "\200\235 he said. \342\200\234I did you a great wrong six years ago, and I need not.\342\200\235"
    "\n\nShe held out her hand to him.\n\n\342\200\234Will you give it me, please?\342\200\235\n\nAnd"
    " for a moment he did not understand.\n\n\342\200\234That fourth feather,\342\200\235 she said.\n"
    "\nHe drew his letter-case from his coat, and shook two feathers out into the palm of his hand. T"
    "he larger one, the ostrich feather, he held out to her. But she said:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200"
    "\234Both.\342\200\235\n\nThere was no reason why he should keep Castleton\342\200\231s feather a"
    "ny longer. He handed them both to her, since she asked for them, and she clasped them, and with "
    "a smile treasured them against her breast.\n\n\342\200\234I have the four feathers now,\342\200"
    "\235 she said.\n\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 answered Feversham; \342\200\234all four. What wi"
    "ll you do with them?\342\200\235\n\nEthne\342\200\231s smile became a laugh.\n\n\342\200\234Do w"
    "ith them!\342\200\235 she cried in scorn. \342\200\234I shall do nothing with them. I shall keep"
    " them. I am very proud to have them to keep.\342\200\235\n\nShe kept them, as she had once kept "
    "Harry Feversham\342\200\231s portrait. There was something perhaps in Durrance\342\200\231s cont"
    "ention that women so much more than men gather up their experiences and live upon them, looking "
    "backwards. Feversham, at all events, would now have dropped the feathers then and there and crus"
    "hed them into the dust of the path with his heel; they had done their work. They could no longer"
    " reproach, they were no longer needed to encourage, they were dead things. Ethne, however, held "
    "them tight in her hand; to her they were not dead.\n\n\342\200\234Colonel Trench was here a fort"
    "night ago,\342\200\235 she said. \342\200\234He told me you were bringing it back to me.\342\200"
    "\235\n\n\342\200\234But he did not know of the fourth feather,\342\200\235 said Feversham. \342"
    "\200\234I never told any man that I had it.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. You told Colonel Tre"
    "nch on your first night in the House of Stone at Omdurman. He told me. I no longer hate him,\342"
    "\200\235 she added, but without a smile and quite seriously, as though it was an important state"
    "ment which needed careful recognition.\n\n\342\200\234I am glad of that,\342\200\235 said Fevers"
    "ham. \342\200\234He is a great friend of mine.\342\200\235\n\nEthne was silent for a moment or t"
    "wo. Then she said:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234I wonder whether you have forgotten our drive from"
    " Ramelton to our house when I came to fetch you from the quay? We were alone in the dogcart, and"
    " we spoke\342\200\224\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Of the friends whom one knows for friends the f"
    "irst moment, and whom one seems to recognise even though one has never seen them before,\342\200"
    "\235 interrupted Feversham. \342\200\234Indeed I remember.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234And whom o"
    "ne never loses whether absent or dead,\342\200\235 continued Ethne. \342\200\234I said that one "
    "could always be sure of such friends, and you answered\342\200\224\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I "
    "answered that one could make mistakes,\342\200\235 again Feversham interrupted.\n\n\342\200\234Y"
    "es, and I disagreed. I said that one might seem to make mistakes, and perhaps think so for a lon"
    "g while, but that in the end one would be proved not to have made them. I have often thought of "
    "those words. I remembered them very clearly when Captain Willoughby brought to me the first feat"
    "her, and with a great deal of remorse. I remember them again very clearly today, although I have"
    " no room in my thoughts for remorse. I was right, you see, and I should have clung firmly to my "
    "faith. But I did not.\342\200\235 Her voice shook a little, and pleaded as she went on: \342\200"
    "\234I was young. I knew very little. I was unaware how little. I judged hastily; but today I und"
    "erstand.\342\200\235\n\nShe opened her hand and gazed for a while at the white feathers. Then sh"
    "e turned and went inside the church. Feversham followed her.";

static const char generated_chapter_content_031[] =
    "Ethne sat down in the corner of a pew next to the aisle, and Feversham took his stand beside her"
    ". It was very quiet and peaceful within that tiny church. The afternoon sun shone through the up"
    "per windows and made a golden haze about the roof. The natural murmurs of the summer floated ple"
    "asantly through the open door.\n\n\342\200\234I am glad that you remembered our drive and what w"
    "e said,\342\200\235 she continued. \342\200\234It is rather important to me that you should reme"
    "mber. Because, although I have got you back, I am going to send you away from me again. You will"
    " be one of the absent friends whom I shall not lose because you are absent.\342\200\235\n\nShe s"
    "poke slowly, looking straight in front of her without faltering. It was a difficult speech for h"
    "er to deliver, but she had thought over it night and day during this last fortnight, and the wor"
    "ds were ready to her lips. At the first sight of Harry Feversham, recovered to her after so many"
    " years, so much suspense, so much suffering, it had seemed to her that she never would be able t"
    "o speak them, however necessary it was that they should be spoken. But as they stood over agains"
    "t one another she had forced herself to remember that necessity until she actually recognised an"
    "d felt it. Then she had gone back into the church and taken a seat, and gathered up her strength"
    ".\n\nIt would be easier for both of them, she thought, if she should give no sign of what so qui"
    "ck a separation cost her. He would know surely enough, and she wished him to know; she wished hi"
    "m to understand that not one moment of his six years, so far as she was concerned, had been spen"
    "t in vain. But that could be understood without the signs of emotion. So she spoke her speech lo"
    "oking steadily straight forward and speaking in an even voice.\n\n\342\200\234I know that you wi"
    "ll mind very much, just as I do. But there is no help for it,\342\200\235 she resumed. \342\200"
    "\234At all events you are at home again, with the right to be at home. It is a great comfort to "
    "me to know that. But there are other, much greater reasons from which we can both take comfort. "
    "Colonel Trench told me enough of your captivity to convince me that we both see with the same ey"
    "es. We both understand that this second parting, hard as it is, is still a very slight, small th"
    "ing compared with the other, our first parting over at the house six years ago. I felt very lone"
    "ly after that, as I shall not feel lonely now. There was a great barrier between us then separat"
    "ing us forever. We should never have met again here or afterwards. I am quite sure of that. But "
    "you have broken the barrier down by all your pain and bravery during these last years. I am no l"
    "ess sure of that. I am absolutely confident about it, and I believe you are too. So that althoug"
    "h we shall not see one another here and as long as we live, the afterwards is quite sure for us "
    "both. And we can wait for that. You can. You have waited with so much strength all these years s"
    "ince we parted. And I can too, for I get strength from your victory.\342\200\235\n\nShe stopped,"
    " and for a while there was silence in that church. To Feversham her words were gracious as rain "
    "upon dry land. To hear her speak them uplifted him so that those six years of trial, of slinking"
    " into corners out of the sight of his fellows, of lonely endurance, of many heart-sinkings and m"
    "uch bodily pain, dwindled away into insignificance. They had indeed borne their fruit to him. Fo"
    "r Ethne had spoken in a gentle voice just what his ears had so often longed to hear as he lay aw"
    "ake at night in the bazaar at Suakin, in the Nile villages, in the dim wide spaces of the desert"
    ", and what he had hardly dared to hope she ever would speak. He stood quite silently by her side"
    ", still hearing her voice though the voice had ceased. Long ago there were certain bitter words "
    "which she had spoken, and he had told Sutch, so closely had they clung and stung, that he believ"
    "ed in his dying moments he would hear them again and so go to his grave with her reproaches ring"
    "ing in his ears. He remembered that prediction of his now and knew that it was false. The words "
    "he would hear would be those which she had just uttered.\n\nFor Ethne\342\200\231s proposal that"
    " they should separate he was not unprepared. He had heard already that she was engaged, and he d"
    "id not argue against her wish. But he understood that she had more to say to him. And she had. B"
    "ut she was slow to speak it. This was the last time she was to see Harry Feversham; she meant re"
    "solutely to send him away. When once he had passed through that church door, through which the s"
    "unlight and the summer murmurs came, and his shadow gone from the threshold, she would never tal"
    "k with him or set her eyes on him until her life was ended. So she deferred the moment of his go"
    "ing by silences and slow speech. It might be so very long before that end came. She had, she tho"
    "ught, the right to protract this one interview. She rather hoped that he would speak of his trav"
    "els, his dangers; she was prepared to discuss at length with him even the politics of the Sudan."
    " But he waited for her.\n\n\342\200\234I am going to be married,\342\200\235 she said at length,"
    " \342\200\234and immediately. I am to marry a friend of yours, Colonel Durrance.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "There was hardly a pause before Feversham answered:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234He has cared for "
    "you a long while. I was not aware of it until I went away, but, thinking over everything, I thou"
    "ght it likely, and in a very little time I became sure.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234He is blind."
    "\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Blind!\342\200\235 exclaimed Feversham. \342\200\234He, of all men, "
    "blind!\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Exactly,\342\200\235 said Ethne. \342\200\234He\342\200\224of "
    "all men. His blindness explains everything\342\200\224why I marry him, why I send you away. It w"
    "as after he went blind that I became engaged to him. It was before Captain Willoughby came to me"
    " with the first feather. It was between those two events. You see, after you went away one thoug"
    "ht over things rather carefully. I used to lie awake and think, and I resolved that two men\342"
    "\200\231s lives should not be spoilt because of me.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Mine was not,\342"
    "\200\235 Feversham interrupted. \342\200\234Please believe that.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Part"
    "ly it was,\342\200\235 she returned, \342\200\234I know very well. You would not own it for my s"
    "ake, but it was. I was determined that a second should not be. And so when Colonel Durrance went"
    " blind\342\200\224you know the man he was, you can understand what blindness meant to him, the l"
    "oss of everything he cared for\342\200\224\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Except you.\342\200\235\n"
    "\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 Ethne answered quietly, \342\200\234except me. So I became engage"
    "d to him. But he has grown very quick\342\200\224you cannot guess how quick. And he sees so very"
    " clearly. A hint tells him the whole hidden truth. At present he knows nothing of the four feath"
    "ers.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Are you sure?\342\200\235 suddenly exclaimed Feversham.\n\n\342"
    "\200\234Yes. Why?\342\200\235 asked Ethne, turning her face towards him for the first time since"
    " she had sat down.\n\n\342\200\234Lieutenant Sutch was at Suakin while I was at Omdurman. He kne"
    "w that I was a prisoner there. He sent messages to me, he tried to organise my escape.\342\200"
    "\235\n\nEthne was startled.\n\n\342\200\234Oh,\342\200\235 she said, \342\200\234Colonel Durranc"
    "e certainly knew that you were in Omdurman. He saw you in Wadi Halfa , and he heard that you had"
    " gone south into the desert. He was distressed about it; he asked a friend to get news of you, a"
    "nd the friend got news that you were in Omdurman. He told me so himself, and\342\200\224yes, he "
    "told me that he would try to arrange for your escape. No doubt he has done that through Lieutena"
    "nt Sutch. He has been at Wiesbaden with an oculist; he only returned a week ago. Otherwise he wo"
    "uld have told me about it. Very likely he was the reason why Lieutenant Sutch was at Suakin, but"
    " he knows nothing of the four feathers. He only knows that our engagement was abruptly broken of"
    "f; he believes that I have no longer any thought of you at all. But if you come back, if you and"
    " I saw anything of each other, however calmly we met, however indifferently we spoke, he would g"
    "uess. He is so quick he would be sure to guess.\342\200\235 She paused for a moment, and added i"
    "n a whisper, \342\200\234And he would guess right.\342\200\235\n\nFeversham saw the blood flush "
    "her forehead and deepen the colour of her cheeks. He did not move from his position, he did not "
    "bend towards her, or even in voice give any sign which would make this leave-taking yet more dif"
    "ficult to carry through.\n\n\342\200\234Yes, I see,\342\200\235 he said. \342\200\234And he must"
    " not guess.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234No, he must not,\342\200\235 returned Ethne. \342\200\234"
    "I am so glad you see that too, Harry. The straight and simple thing is the only thing for us to "
    "do. He must never guess, for, as you said, he has nothing left but me.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234Is Durrance here?\342\200\235 asked Feversham.\n\n\342\200\234He is staying at the vicarage."
    "\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Very well,\342\200\235 he said. \342\200\234It is only fair that I s"
    "hould tell you I had no thought that you would wait. I had no wish that you should; I had no rig"
    "ht to such a wish. When you gave me that fourth feather in the little room at Ramelton, with the"
    " music coming faintly through the door, I understood your meaning. There was to be a complete, a"
    "n irrevocable end. We were not to be the merest acquaintances. So I said nothing to you of the p"
    "lan which came clear and definite into my mind at the very time when you gave me the feathers. Y"
    "ou see, I might never have succeeded. I might have died trying to succeed. I might even perhaps "
    "have shirked the attempt. It would be time enough for me to speak if I came back. So I never for"
    "med any wish that you should wait.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234That was what Colonel Trench told "
    "me.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I told him that too?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234On your first nig"
    "ht in the House of Stone.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Well, it\342\200\231s just the truth. The m"
    "ost I hoped for\342\200\224and I did hope for that every hour of every day\342\200\224was that, "
    "if I did come home, you would take back your feather, and that we might\342\200\224not renew our"
    " friendship here, but see something of one another afterwards.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes,"
    "\342\200\235 said Ethne. \342\200\234Then there will be no parting.\342\200\235\n\nEthne spoke v"
    "ery simply, without even a sigh, but she looked at Harry Feversham as she spoke and smiled. The "
    "look and the smile told him what the cost of the separation would be to her. And, understanding "
    "what it meant now, he understood, with an infinitely greater completeness than he had ever reach"
    "ed in his lonely communings, what it must have meant six years ago when she was left with her pr"
    "ide stricken as sorely as her heart.\n\n\342\200\234What trouble you must have gone through!\342"
    "\200\235 he cried, and she turned and looked him over.\n\n\342\200\234Not I alone,\342\200\235 s"
    "he said gently. \342\200\234I passed no nights in the House of Stone.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234But it was my fault. Do you remember what you said when the morning came through the blinds?"
    " \342\200\230It\342\200\231s not right that one should suffer so much pain.\342\200\231 It was n"
    "ot right.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I had forgotten the words\342\200\224oh, a long time since"
    "\342\200\224until Colonel Trench reminded me. I should never have spoken them. When I did I was "
    "not thinking they would live so in your thoughts. I am sorry that I spoke them.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234Oh, they were just enough. I never blamed you for them,\342\200\235 said Feversham, "
    "with a laugh. \342\200\234I used to think that they would be the last words I should hear when I"
    " turned my face to the wall. But you have given me others today wherewith to replace them.\342"
    "\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Thank you,\342\200\235 she said quietly.\n\nThere was nothing more to be"
    " said, and Feversham wondered why Ethne did not rise from her seat in the pew. It did not occur "
    "to him to talk of his travels or adventures. The occasion seemed too serious, too vital. They we"
    "re together to decide the most solemn issue in their lives. Once the decision was made, as now i"
    "t had been made, he felt that they could hardly talk on other topics. Ethne, however, still kept"
    " him at her side. Though she sat so calmly and still, though her face was quiet in its look of g"
    "ravity, her heart ached with longing. Just for a little longer, she pleaded to herself. The sunl"
    "ight was withdrawing from the walls of the church. She measured out a space upon the walls where"
    " it still glowed bright. When all that space was cold grey stone, she would send Harry Feversham"
    " away.\n\n\342\200\234I am glad that you escaped from Omdurman without the help of Lieutenant Su"
    "tch or Colonel Durrance. I wanted so much that everything should be done by you alone without an"
    "ybody\342\200\231s help or interference,\342\200\235 she said, and after she had spoken there fo"
    "llowed a silence. Once or twice she looked towards the wall, and each time she saw the space of "
    "golden light narrowed, and knew that her minutes were running out. \342\200\234You suffered horr"
    "ibly at Dongola ,\342\200\235 she said in a low voice. \342\200\234Colonel Trench told me.\342"
    "\200\235\n\n\342\200\234What does it matter now?\342\200\235 Feversham answered. \342\200\234Tha"
    "t time seems rather far away to me.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Had you anything of mine with you"
    "?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I had your white feather.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234But anything e"
    "lse? Any little thing which I had given you in the other days?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Nothin"
    "g.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I had your photograph,\342\200\235 she said. \342\200\234I kept it"
    ".\342\200\235\n\nFeversham suddenly leaned down towards her.\n\n\342\200\234You did!\342\200\235"
    "\n\nEthne nodded her head.\n\n\342\200\234Yes. The moment I went upstairs that night I packed up"
    " your presents and addressed them to your rooms.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes, I got them in L"
    "ondon.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234But I put your photograph aside first of all to keep. I burnt "
    "all your letters after I had addressed the parcel and taken it down to the hall to be sent away."
    " I had just finished burning your letters when I heard your step upon the gravel in the early mo"
    "rning underneath my windows. But I had already put your photograph aside. I have it now. I shall"
    " keep it and the feathers together.\342\200\235 She added after a moment:\342\200\224\n\n\342"
    "\200\234I rather wish that you had had something of mine with you all the time.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234I had no right to anything,\342\200\235 said Feversham.\n\nThere was still a narrow "
    "slip of gold upon the grey space of stone.\n\n\342\200\234What will you do now?\342\200\235 she "
    "asked.\n\n\342\200\234I shall go home first and see my father. It will depend upon the way we me"
    "et.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234You will let Colonel Durrance know. I would like to hear about it"
    ".\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes, I will write to Durrance.\342\200\235\n\nThe slip of gold was "
    "gone, the clear light of a summer evening filled the church, a light without radiance or any col"
    "our.\n\n\342\200\234I shall not see you for a long while,\342\200\235 said Ethne, and for the fi"
    "rst time her voice broke in a sob. \342\200\234I shall not have a letter from you again.\342\200"
    "\235\n\nShe leaned a little forward and bent her head, for the tears had gathered in her eyes. B"
    "ut she rose up bravely from her seat, and together they went out of the church side by side. She"
    " leaned towards him as they walked so that they touched.\n\nFeversham untied his horse and mount"
    "ed it. As his foot touched the stirrup Ethne caught her dog close to her.\n\n\342\200\234Goodbye"
    ",\342\200\235 she said. She did not now even try to smile, she held out her hand to him. He took"
    " it and bent down from his saddle close to her. She kept her eyes steadily upon him though the t"
    "ears brimmed in them.\n\n\342\200\234Goodbye,\342\200\235 he said. He held her hand just for a l"
    "ittle while, and then releasing it, rode down the hill. He rode for a hundred yards, stopped and"
    " looked back. Ethne had stopped, too, and with this space between them and their faces towards o"
    "ne another they remained. Ethne made no sign of recognition or farewell. She just stood and look"
    "ed. Then she turned away and went up the village street towards her house alone and very slowly."
    " Feversham watched her till she went in at the gate, but she became dim and blurred to his visio"
    "n before even she had reached there. He was able to see, however, that she did not look back aga"
    "in.\n\nHe rode down the hill. The bad thing which he had done so long ago was not even by his si"
    "x years of labour to be destroyed. It was still to live, its consequence was to be sorrow till t"
    "he end of life for another than himself. That she took the sorrow bravely and without complaint,"
    " doing the straight and simple thing as her loyal nature bade her, did not diminish Harry Fevers"
    "ham\342\200\231s remorse. On the contrary it taught him yet more clearly that she least of all d"
    "eserved unhappiness. The harm was irreparable. Other women might have forgotten, but not she. Fo"
    "r Ethne was of those who neither lightly feel nor lightly forget, and if they love cannot love w"
    "ith half a heart. She would be alone now, he knew, in spite of her marriage, alone up to the ver"
    "y end and at the actual moment of death.";

static const char generated_chapter_content_032[] =
    "The incredible words were spoken that evening. Ethne went into her farmhouse and sat down in the"
    " parlour. She felt cold that summer evening and had the fire lighted. She sat gazing into the br"
    "ight coals with that stillness of attitude which was a sure sign with her of tense emotion. The "
    "moment so eagerly looked for had come, and it was over. She was alone now in her remote little v"
    "illage, out of the world in the hills, and more alone than she had been since Willoughby sailed "
    "on that August morning down the Salcombe estuary. From the time of Willoughby\342\200\231s comin"
    "g she had looked forward night and day to the one half-hour during which Harry Feversham would b"
    "e with her. The half-hour had come and passed. She knew now how she had counted upon its coming,"
    " how she had lived for it. She felt lonely in a rather empty world. But it was part of her natur"
    "e that she had foreseen this sense of loneliness; she had known that there would be a bad hour f"
    "or her after she had sent Harry Feversham away, that all her heart and soul would clamour to her"
    " to call him back. And she forced herself, as she sat shivering by the fire, to remember that sh"
    "e had always foreseen and had always looked beyond it. Tomorrow she would know again that they h"
    "ad not parted forever, tomorrow she would compare the parting of today with the parting on the n"
    "ight of the ball at Lennon House, and recognise what a small thing this was to that. She fell to"
    " wondering what Harry Feversham would do now that he had returned, and while she was building up"
    " for him a future of great distinction she felt Dermod\342\200\231s old collie dog nuzzling at h"
    "er hand with his sure instinct that his mistress was in distress. Ethne rose from her chair and "
    "took the dog\342\200\231s head between her hands and kissed it. He was very old, she thought; he"
    " would die soon and leave her, and then there would be years and years, perhaps, before she lay "
    "down in her bed and knew the great moment was at hand.\n\nThere came a knock upon the door, and "
    "a servant told her that Colonel Durrance was waiting.\n\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 she said, "
    "and as he entered the room she went forward to meet him. She did not shirk the part which she ha"
    "d allotted to herself. She stepped out from the secret chamber of her grief as soon as she was s"
    "ummoned.\n\nShe talked with her visitor as though no unusual thing had happened an hour before, "
    "she even talked of their marriage and the rebuilding of Lennon House. It was difficult, but she "
    "had grown used to difficulties. Only that night Durrance made her path a little harder to tread."
    " He asked her, after the maid had brought in the tea, to play to him the \342\200\234 Melusine O"
    "verture \342\200\235 upon her violin.\n\n\342\200\234Not tonight,\342\200\235 said Ethne. \342"
    "\200\234I am rather tired.\342\200\235 And she had hardly spoken before she changed her mind. Et"
    "hne was determined that in the small things as well as in the great she must not shirk. The smal"
    "l things with their daily happenings were just those about which she must be most careful. \342"
    "\200\234Still I think that I can play the overture,\342\200\235 she said with a smile, and she t"
    "ook down her violin. She played the overture through from the beginning to the end. Durrance sto"
    "od at the window with his back towards her until she had ended. Then he walked to her side.\n\n"
    "\342\200\234I was rather a brute,\342\200\235 he said quietly, \342\200\234to ask you to play th"
    "at overture tonight.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234I wasn\342\200\231t anxious to play,\342\200\235"
    " she answered as she laid the violin aside.\n\n\342\200\234I know. But I was anxious to find out"
    " something, and I knew no other way of finding it out.\342\200\235\n\nEthne turned up to him a s"
    "tartled face.\n\n\342\200\234What do you mean?\342\200\235 she asked in a voice of suspense.\n\n"
    "\342\200\234You are so seldom off your guard. Only indeed at rare times when you play. Once befo"
    "re when you played that overture you were off your guard. I thought that if I could get you to p"
    "lay it again tonight\342\200\224the overture which was once strummed out in a dingy caf\303\251 "
    "at Wadi Halfa \342\200\224tonight again I should find you off your guard.\342\200\235\n\nHis wor"
    "ds took her breath away and the colour from her cheeks. She got up slowly from her chair and sta"
    "red at him wide-eyed. He could not know. It was impossible. He did not know.\n\nBut Durrance wen"
    "t quietly on.\n\n\342\200\234Well? Did you take back your feather? The fourth one?\342\200\235\n"
    "\nThese to Ethne were the incredible words. Durrance spoke them with a smile upon his face. It t"
    "ook her a long time to understand that he had actually spoken them. She was not sure at the firs"
    "t that her overstrained senses were not playing her tricks; but he repeated his question, and sh"
    "e could no longer disbelieve or misunderstand.\n\n\342\200\234Who told you of any fourth feather"
    "?\342\200\235 she asked.\n\n\342\200\234Trench,\342\200\235 he answered. \342\200\234I met him a"
    "t Dover. But he only told me of the fourth feather,\342\200\235 said Durrance. \342\200\234I kne"
    "w of the three before. Trench would never have told me of the fourth had I not known of the thre"
    "e. For I should not have met him as he landed from the steamer at Dover. I should not have asked"
    " him, \342\200\230Where is Harry Feversham?\342\200\231 And for me to know of the three was enou"
    "gh.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234How do you know?\342\200\235 she cried in a kind of despair, and "
    "coming close to her he took gently hold of her arm.\n\n\342\200\234But since I know,\342\200\235"
    " he protested, \342\200\234what does it matter how I know? I have known a long while, ever since"
    " Captain Willoughby came to The Pool with the first feather. I waited to tell you that I knew un"
    "til Harry Feversham came back, and he came today.\342\200\235\n\nEthne sat down in her chair aga"
    "in. She was stunned by Durrance\342\200\231s unexpected disclosure. She had so carefully guarded"
    " her secret, that to realise that for a year it had been no secret came as a shock to her. But, "
    "even in the midst of her confusion, she understood that she must have time to gather up her facu"
    "lties again under command. So she spoke of the unimportant thing to gain the time.\n\n\342\200"
    "\234You were in the church, then? Or you heard us upon the steps? Or you met\342\200\224him as h"
    "e rode away?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Not one of the conjectures is right,\342\200\235 said Du"
    "rrance, with a smile. Ethne had hit upon the right subject to delay the statement of the decisio"
    "n to which she knew very well that he had come. Durrance had his vanities like others; and in pa"
    "rticular one vanity which had sprung up within him since he had become blind. He prided himself "
    "upon the quickness of his perception. It was a delight to him to make discoveries which no one e"
    "xpected a man who had lost his sight to make, and to announce them unexpectedly. It was an addit"
    "ional pleasure to relate to his puzzled audience the steps by which he had reached his discovery"
    ". \342\200\234Not one of your conjectures is right, Ethne,\342\200\235 he said, and he practical"
    "ly asked her to question him.\n\n\342\200\234Then how did you find out?\342\200\235 she asked.\n"
    "\n\342\200\234I knew from Trench that Harry Feversham would come some day, and soon. I passed th"
    "e church this afternoon. Your collie dog barked at me. So I knew you were inside. But a saddled "
    "horse was tied up beside the gate. So someone else was with you, and not anyone from the village"
    ". Then I got you to play, and that told me who it was who rode the horse.\342\200\235\n\n\342"
    "\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 said Ethne, vaguely. She had barely listened to his words. \342\200\234"
    "Yes, I see.\342\200\235 Then in a definite voice, which showed that she had regained all her sel"
    "f-control, she said:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234You went away to Wiesbaden for a year. You went "
    "away just after Captain Willoughby came. Was that the reason why you went away?\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234I went because neither you nor I could have kept up the game of pretences we were pl"
    "aying. You were pretending that you had no thought for Harry Feversham, that you hardly cared wh"
    "ether he was alive or dead. I was pretending not to have found out that beyond everything in the"
    " world you cared for him. Some day or other we should have failed, each one in turn. I dared not"
    " fail, nor dared you. I could not let you, who had said \342\200\230Two lives must not be spoilt"
    " because of me,\342\200\231 live through a year thinking that two lives had been spoilt. You on "
    "your side dared not let me, who had said \342\200\230Marriage between a blind man and a woman is"
    " only possible when there is more than friendship on both sides,\342\200\231 know that upon one "
    "side there was only friendship, and we were so near to failing. So I went away.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234You did not fail,\342\200\235 said Ethne, quietly; \342\200\234it was only I who fai"
    "led.\342\200\235\n\nShe blamed herself most bitterly. She had set herself, as the one thing wort"
    "h doing, and incumbent on her to do, to guard this man from knowledge which would set the crown "
    "on his calamities, and she had failed. He had set himself to protect her from the comprehension "
    "that she had failed, and he had succeeded. It was not any mere sense of humiliation, due to the "
    "fact that the man whom she had thought to hoodwink had hoodwinked her, which troubled her. But s"
    "he felt that she ought to have succeeded, since by failure she had robbed him of his last chance"
    " of happiness. There lay the sting for her.\n\n\342\200\234But it was not your fault,\342\200"
    "\235 he said. \342\200\234Once or twice, as I said, you were off your guard, but the convincing "
    "facts were not revealed to me in that way. When you played the \342\200\230 Melusine Overture "
    "\342\200\231 before, on the night of the day when Willoughby brought you such good news, I took "
    "to myself that happiness of yours which inspired your playing. You must not blame yourself. On t"
    "he contrary, you should be glad that I have found out.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Glad!\342\200"
    "\235 she exclaimed.\n\n\342\200\234Yes, for my sake, glad.\342\200\235 And as she looked at him "
    "in wonderment he went on: \342\200\234Two lives should not be spoilt because of you. Had you had"
    " your way, had I not found out, not two but three lives would have been spoilt because of you"
    "\342\200\224because of your loyalty.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Three?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234Yours. Yes\342\200\224yes, yours, Feversham\342\200\231s, and mine. It was hard enough to ke"
    "ep the pretence during the few weeks we were in Devonshire. Own to it, Ethne! When I went to Lon"
    "don to see my oculist it was a relief; it gave you a pause, a rest wherein to drop pretence and "
    "be yourself. It could not have lasted long even in Devonshire. But what when we came to live und"
    "er the same roof, and there were no visits to the oculist, when we saw each other every hour of "
    "every day? Sooner or later the truth must have come to me. It might have come gradually, a suspi"
    "cion added to a suspicion and another to that until no doubt was left. Or it might have flashed "
    "out in one terrible moment. But it would have been made clear. And then, Ethne? What then? You a"
    "imed at a compensation; you wanted to make up to me for the loss of what I love\342\200\224my ca"
    "reer, the army, the special service in the strange quarters of the world. A fine compensation to"
    " sit in front of you knowing you had married a cripple out of pity, and that in so doing you had"
    " crippled yourself and foregone the happiness which is yours by right. Whereas now\342\200\224"
    "\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Whereas now?\342\200\235 she repeated.\n\n\342\200\234I remain your "
    "friend, which I would rather be than your unloved husband,\342\200\235 he said very gently.\n\nE"
    "thne made no rejoinder. The decision had been taken out of her hands.\n\n\342\200\234You sent Ha"
    "rry away this afternoon,\342\200\235 said Durrance. \342\200\234You said goodbye to him twice."
    "\342\200\235\n\nAt the \342\200\234twice\342\200\235 Ethne raised her head, but before she could"
    " speak Durrance explained:\342\200\224\n\n\342\200\234Once in the church, again upon your violin"
    ",\342\200\235 and he took up the instrument from the chair on which she had laid it. \342\200"
    "\234It has been a very good friend, your violin,\342\200\235 he said. \342\200\234A good friend "
    "to me, to us all. You will understand that, Ethne, very soon. I stood at the window while you pl"
    "ayed it. I had never heard anything in my life half so sad as your farewell to Harry Feversham, "
    "and yet it was nobly sad. It was true music, it did not complain.\342\200\235 He laid the violin"
    " down upon the chair again.\n\n\342\200\234I am going to send a messenger to Rathmullen. Harry c"
    "annot cross Lough Swilly tonight. The messenger will bring him back tomorrow.\342\200\235\n\nIt "
    "had been a day of many emotions and surprises for Ethne. As Durrance bent down towards her, he b"
    "ecame aware that she was crying silently. For once tears had their way with her. He took his cap"
    " and walked noiselessly to the door of the room. As he opened it, Ethne got up.\n\n\342\200\234D"
    "on\342\200\231t go for a moment,\342\200\235 she said, and she left the fireplace and came to th"
    "e centre of the room.\n\n\342\200\234The oculist at Wiesbaden?\342\200\235 she asked. \342\200"
    "\234He gave you a hope?\342\200\235\n\nDurrance stood meditating whether he should lie or speak "
    "the truth.\n\n\342\200\234No,\342\200\235 he said at length. \342\200\234There is no hope. But I"
    " am not so helpless as at one time I was afraid that I should be. I can get about, can\342\200"
    "\231t I? Perhaps one of these days I shall go on a journey, one of the long journeys amongst the"
    " strange people in the east.\342\200\235\n\nHe went from the house upon his errand. He had learn"
    "ed his lesson a long time since, and the violin had taught it him. It had spoken again that afte"
    "rnoon, and though with a different voice, had offered to him the same message. The true music ca"
    "nnot complain.";

static const char generated_chapter_content_033[] =
    "In the early summer of next year two old men sat reading their newspapers after breakfast upon t"
    "he terrace of Broad Place. The elder of the two turned over a sheet.\n\n\342\200\234I see Osman "
    "Digna\342\200\231s back at Suakin,\342\200\235 said he. \342\200\234There\342\200\231s likely to"
    " be some fighting.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Oh,\342\200\235 said the other, \342\200\234he wil"
    "l not do much harm.\342\200\235 And he laid down his paper. The quiet English countryside vanish"
    "ed from before his eyes. He saw only the white city by the Red Sea shimmering in the heat, the b"
    "rown plains about it with their tangle of halfa grass, and in the distance the hills towards Kho"
    "r Gwob .\n\n\342\200\234A stuffy place Suakin, eh, Sutch?\342\200\235 said General Feversham.\n"
    "\n\342\200\234Appallingly stuffy. I heard of an officer who went down on parade at six o\342\200"
    "\231clock of the morning there, sunstruck in the temples right through a regulation helmet. Yes,"
    " a town of dank heat! But I was glad to be there\342\200\224very glad,\342\200\235 he said with "
    "some feeling.\n\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 said Feversham, briskly; \342\200\234ibex, eh?\342"
    "\200\235\n\n\342\200\234No,\342\200\235 replied Sutch. \342\200\234All the ibex had been shot of"
    "f by the English garrison for miles round.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234No? Something to do, then."
    " That\342\200\231s it?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes, that\342\200\231s it, Feversham. Somethin"
    "g to do.\342\200\235\n\nAnd both men busied themselves again over their papers. But in a little "
    "while a footman brought to each a small pile of letters. General Feversham ran over his envelope"
    "s with a quick eye, selected one letter, and gave a grunt of satisfaction. He took a pair of spe"
    "ctacles from a case and placed them upon his nose.\n\n\342\200\234From Ramelton?\342\200\235 ask"
    "ed Sutch, dropping his newspaper on to the terrace.\n\n\342\200\234From Ramelton,\342\200\235 an"
    "swered Feversham. \342\200\234I\342\200\231ll light a cigar first.\342\200\235\n\nHe laid the le"
    "tter down on the garden table which stood between his companion and himself, drew a cigar-case f"
    "rom his pocket, and in spite of the impatience of Lieutenant Sutch, proceeded to cut and light i"
    "t with the utmost deliberation. The old man had become an epicure in this respect. A letter from"
    " Ramelton was a luxury to be enjoyed with all the accessories of comfort which could be obtained"
    ". He made himself comfortable in his chair, stretched out his legs, and smoked enough of his cig"
    "ar to assure himself that it was drawing well. Then he took up his letter again and opened it.\n"
    "\n\342\200\234From him?\342\200\235 asked Sutch.\n\n\342\200\234No; from her.\342\200\235\n\n"
    "\342\200\234Ah!\342\200\235\n\nGeneral Feversham read the letter through slowly, while Lieutenan"
    "t Sutch tried not to peep at it across the table. When the general had finished he turned back t"
    "o the first page, and began it again.\n\n\342\200\234Any news?\342\200\235 said Sutch, with a ca"
    "sual air.\n\n\342\200\234They are very pleased with the house now that it\342\200\231s rebuilt."
    "\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Anything more?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. Harry\342\200\231s fi"
    "nished the sixth chapter of his history of the war.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Good!\342\200\235"
    " said Sutch. \342\200\234You\342\200\231ll see, he\342\200\231ll do that well. He has imaginatio"
    "n, he knows the ground, he was present while the war went on. Moreover, he was in the bazaars, h"
    "e saw the under side of it.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. But you and I won\342\200\231t read "
    "it, Sutch,\342\200\235 said Feversham. \342\200\234No; I am wrong. You may, for you can give me "
    "a good many years.\342\200\235\n\nHe turned back to his letter and again Sutch asked:\342\200"
    "\224\n\n\342\200\234Anything more?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes. They are coming here in a for"
    "tnight.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Good,\342\200\235 said Sutch. \342\200\234I shall stay.\342"
    "\200\235\n\nHe took a turn along the terrace and came back. He saw Feversham sitting with the le"
    "tter upon his knees and a frown of great perplexity upon his face.\n\n\342\200\234You know, Sutc"
    "h, I never understood,\342\200\235 he said. \342\200\234Did you?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes,"
    " I think I did.\342\200\235\n\nSutch did not try to explain. It was as well, he thought, that Fe"
    "versham never would understand. For he could not understand without much self-reproach.\n\n\342"
    "\200\234Do you ever see Durrance?\342\200\235 asked the general, suddenly.\n\n\342\200\234Yes, I"
    " see a good deal of Durrance. He is abroad just now.\342\200\235\n\nFeversham turned towards his"
    " friend.\n\n\342\200\234He came to Broad Place when you went to Suakin, and talked to me for hal"
    "f an hour. He was Harry\342\200\231s best man. Well, that too I never understood. Did you?\342"
    "\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Yes, I understood that as well.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200\234Oh!\342\200"
    "\235 said General Feversham. He asked for no explanations, but, as he had always done, he took t"
    "he questions which he did not understand and put them aside out of his thoughts. But he did not "
    "turn to his other letters. He sat smoking his cigar, and looked out across the summer country an"
    "d listened to the sounds rising distantly from the fields. Sutch had read through all of his cor"
    "respondence before Feversham spoke again.\n\n\342\200\234I have been thinking,\342\200\235 he sa"
    "id. \342\200\234Have you noticed the date of the month, Sutch?\342\200\235 and Sutch looked up q"
    "uickly.\n\n\342\200\234Yes,\342\200\235 said he, \342\200\234this day next week will be the anni"
    "versary of our attack upon the Redan, and Harry\342\200\231s birthday.\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234Exactly,\342\200\235 replied Feversham. \342\200\234Why shouldn\342\200\231t we start the Cr"
    "imean nights again?\342\200\235\n\nSutch jumped up from his chair.\n\n\342\200\234Splendid!\342"
    "\200\235 he cried. \342\200\234Can we muster a tableful, do you think?\342\200\235\n\n\342\200"
    "\234Let\342\200\231s see,\342\200\235 said Feversham, and ringing a handbell upon the table, sen"
    "t the servant for the Army List. Bending over that Army List the two veterans may be left.\n\nBu"
    "t of one other figure in this story a final word must be said. That night, when the invitations "
    "had been sent out from Broad Place, and no longer a light gleamed from any window of the house, "
    "a man leaned over the rail of a steamer anchored at Port Said and listened to the song of the Ar"
    "ab coolies as they tramped up and down the planks with their coal baskets between the barges and"
    " the ship\342\200\231s side. The clamour of the streets of the town came across the water to his"
    " ears. He pictured to himself the flare of braziers upon the quays, the lighted portholes, and d"
    "ark funnels ahead and behind in the procession of the anchored ships. Attended by a servant, he "
    "had come back to the east again. Early the next morning the steamer moved through the canal, and"
    " towards the time of sunset passed out into the chills of the Gulf of Suez. Kassassin, Tel-el-Ke"
    "bir, Tamai, Tamanieb , the attack upon McNeil\342\200\231s zeriba\342\200\224Durrance lived agai"
    "n through the good years of his activity, the years of plenty. Within that country on the west t"
    "he long preparations were going steadily forward which would one day roll up the Dervish Empire "
    "and crush it into dust. Upon the glacis of the ruined fort of Sinkat , Durrance had promised him"
    "self to take a hand in that great work, but the desert which he loved had smitten and cast him o"
    "ut. But at all events the boat steamed southwards into the Red Sea. Three nights more, and thoug"
    "h he would not see it, the Southern Cross would lift slantwise into the sky.";

